request.description: ... unfortunately, there is no nice REST API for the [Octodex ](https://octodex.github.com) \- GitHub's home of Octocat illustrations and the place where superfans can find and share their favorite designs. First, we have called [https://octodex.github.com](https://octodex.github.com) and asked Postbot to parse the html response and visualize the results using the following prompts: > Visualize the response by displaying the pictures in the a.d-block img data-src elements and prepend [https://octodex.github.com](https://octodex.github.com/) > Improve the visualization by adding a title to the top of the images - the title can be found in the a.d-block img.alt element We also like to include the authors of the various octocat designs. As most of them are displayed using their GitHub profile page, we ask Postbot to extract their name from the profile. > Display the authors of the octocats below the title, authors always start with prefix [https://github.com/](https://github.com/), that prefix should be removed, entries without that prefix should get ignored Finally, we like to save the parsed results in a Json structure, that is much easier to understand by other programs and can be used to write easy API tests. > Store the authors, title, absolute url of all pictures into a json structure and save the stringified version of that structure as a collection variable named octodexJson for the next request, the json field containing the url should be called octocat You do not need to repeat those prompts as we already included the generated test code for you - just send the request and have a look at the visualization tab.

request.description: The [Postman Echo API service](https://www.postman.com/postman/workspace/published-postman-templates/collection/631643-f695cab7-6878-eb55-7943-ad88e1ccfd65?action=share&source=copy-link&creator=24483733) can be used to return the JSON structure created by Postbot in the previous request - check out the body tab content to learn how this works. Now, that we have the octocats in proper format, we like to ask Postbot again to visualize the results, but this time, there will be no additional help on how to parse the returned data structures. You should see a table similar to the one in the screenshot that is rendered based on the test code that Postbot generated. Postbot seemed to have temporarily forgotten Mona, we need to tell it again that the Octocat column is actually a picture of its Octocat friends, so let's prompt it to improve the visualization. It's time to finally create some API tests - first, we like make sure we get 100 octocats in less than a second. We like to ensure that every Octocat illustration has at least one author, let's ask Postbot exactly that. As it turns out, the Original octocat did not have an author with a GitHub profile, we need to tell Postbot about Simon Oxley - who did not only invent the original Octocat but also the Twitter and Digital Ocean mascot to exclude him from the test to make it pass. Now, that all tests are passing again, we like to know who created most Octocat illustrations and if there are some designers who only created a few - this request already requires some counting logic - will Postbot manage? There are 8 designers who created one illustration and Cameron created the most. To show that Postman can also create tests with algorithmitically challenging logic, we will ask it to master one last challenge, namely to show the designers that collaborated the most when designing Octocats. Now that you know that John and Tony collaborated the most, it's time to collaborate with your team again and buildyour own backend for the Octodex REST API - as API design is a team sport üòªü§ñüòä.

request.description: JSON is so much easier to work with than HTML, so why not create your own Octodex REST API that returns JSON? We have already created a Postman [API Mock Server](https://learning.postman.com/docs/designing-and-developing-your-api/mocking-data/setting-up-mock/) and copied all the tests and visualizations created by Postbot in this request. Once you have created your real backend, just replace the value of the `url` collection variable with the URL of your own server and run the tests again. If you are interested in how you can design your own APIs with Postman, version them in GitHub, include CI/CD and generate server boilerplate code, [check out our documentation](https://learning.postman.com/docs/designing-and-developing-your-api/the-api-workflow/). If you like to start with a working OpenAPI definition, [this Postman API ](https://www.postman.com/automotive-demo/workspace/my-workspace/api/012ac499-eafb-489b-af7e-66a2d01896d6) has you covered.
